author: @sharonchetia54
text: Hi Corey, please help me understand series mutability. I was trying the below and not sure what is going on here. From what i can see changing both value and size is possible as series id remains same . What changes is array memory. But if series are value mutable, the array id should not change correct? I am so confused.  # Chaning value in Series- The series memory is same but array memory is different  my_sr=pd.Series([1,2,3]) print('Original series location:',id(my_sr)) print('Original series-array location:',id(my_sr.array))   my_sr[1]=22 print('New series location:',id(my_sr)) print('New series-array location',id(my_sr.array))  #------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ #Changing size in Series- The series memory is same but Array location changes  x=pd.Series([1,2,3])  print('Original series location:',id(x))        # Series memory location print('Original series-array location:',id(x.array))  # Array memory location   x[3]="Apple"        #Increasing size by adding anew element print('New series location:',id(x))        # Series memory location print('New series-array location',id(x.array))  # Array memory location

author: @sumitkumarmahto5081
text: One clarification here, if you do slicing using iloc, the end index is not inclusive, that is, if you run a command df.iloc[0:2, 1], this would return only the first 2 rows (works just like core Python). Whereas in case of loc, it returns the end index (returns all 3 rows for above example), which is very well explained by Corey.

author: @michalbotor
text: i don't know if it's a bug or it's intentional (certainly it's confusing), but df.iloc[0:2] will return you rows 0 and 1 but not 2, whereas df.loc[0:2] will return you rows 0, 1 and 2. edit. oh, i get it now. when i use df.iloc[0:2] i'm working on integers 0, 1 and 2 and therefore python logic of inclusive:exclusive applies. however when i'm using df.loc[0:2] i'm working on labels '0,' '1' and '2' and therefore language logic of inclusive:inclusive applies, as in "I'm working from Monday to Friday." means that i'm working on Friday as well.
